<li><h4>Oxygen Tank Exhaustion Timer</h4>
During our senior year of high school, myself and two partners (Lucas Hudson and Hayden Herzberger) created a count-down timer for pressurized gas tanks. We were initially inspired when we wanted
a way to help aging COPD (Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease) patients worry less about their supplementary oxygen tanks running low.

The device is able to measure pressure changes and calculate an estimated time-until-depletion within a few seconds of testing. The estimate was calculated on an Arduino UNO and displayed on an LCD mounted to the device. Auditory alarms
activated at set warning points. I also used a second arduino with a nano-router to host a local Wi-Fi network so any device could receive the estimate.

We applied for a US utility patent on the device, although our interests have changed since graduating and working on new projects.

<hr />
<li><h4>Gimbaled Nerf Turret with Facial Detection</h4>
This project was completed entirely by myself and two friends - Lucas Hudson and Ryan Turner. While brainstorming fun things to make, we came up with the simple thought: what would be the most
surprising thing our friend could open the door and see? The obvious answer is a moving Nerf blaster with a laser diode following his chest and pelting him with darts.

The idea stuck and we began our work. I handled the facial detection components. I taught myself how the OpenCV library worked and created a framework to manage our project. Furthermore, I began learning
about CMake to simplify our build process (that came in handy) and practiced Git with our shared GitHub repo.

Before we disassemble the project for parts, I'm going to try my hand at training the facial detection algorithm on my own face. I've always been fascinated by computer vision and this has been a very
entertaining way to play around with it.

<hr />
<li><h4>Infix/Postfix Calculator</h4>
Although simple, this was my first major C++ development and something of which I'm proud. Completed as an honors contract for my CS2433 (C/C++ Programming) course, this program creates an
Infix notation (5 + 5 = 10) or a Postfix notation (also known as Reverse Polish Notation | 5 5 + = 10) calculator in the terminal. The user can specify input or output files if desired and store
constants and variables for future use.

The Postfix notation is implemented as a stack, while the Infix notation uses a recursive descent parser to evaluate any number of nested parenthetical expressions. Unfortunately this also means the
Infix style ignores the order of operations. Quite a glaring problem! I may come back someday to implement another method of Infix calculation, in order to abide by PEMDAS.

<hr />
<li><h4>Peer-to-Peer Battleship</h4>
I created an online multiplayer version of Battleship, complete with functioning chat protocol and GUI using Java. The project was completed as an honors contract for my CS1113 (Java 1) course
during my Freshman year of college. The simplicity of the game itself allowed me to focus on the more interesting aspects of the project: socket networking and GUI development. I was new
to both concepts, but quickly became more familiar with the idiosyncrasies of the Java Swing and Net libraries.

I hope to come back to this project with more experience - potentially as a way to learn the Unity game engine and C#.
